ce:section.ce:para:
The main parameters affecting the fluorescence quenching of S,N-GQDs by glimepiride were optimized using a Box-Behnken experimental design. Initial one-factor-at-a-time experiments were conducted to identify the critical factors and their respective ranges. The selected factors were pH of the medium (5–9), volume of the buffer added (1–3 mL), S,N-GQDs concentration represented as volume (0.5–2 mL), and incubation time (1–8 min). The experimental design consisted of 29 experimental runs, including 5 center points, to evaluate the main effects, quadratic effects and possible interactions between the studied factors (
                           Table S1
                        ). The response variable was the quenching efficiency (F0/F) of the S,N-GQDs-glimepiride system. ANOVA analysis followed by backward elimination was used to establish the final model and identify the significant factors. The experimental design matrix and the resulting data were analyzed using Design-Expert software.

The regression model was further validated by examining different set of parameters such as coefficient of determination (R2), adjusted R2, predicted R2 and lack of fit test. The high R2 value of 0.9714, adjusted R2 of 0.9618 and predicted R2 of 0.9406 along with the non-significant lack of fit test (p > 0.05) confirm the adequacy of the quadratic model to accurately predict the fluorescence quenching response within the experimental domain. The high adequate precision ratio of 34.949 with low CV% 3.75 suggests a satisfactory signal-to-noise ratio and high reliability of the proposed model, further validating the reliability of the model. Residual plots verified the normality of the data, and the straight line between the observed and predicted values indicated the goodness of fit (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). Regarding the effect of run order of the experiments, no trends were observed, implying that potential external factors did not significantly influence the response (
                           Fig. S3
                        ).

Finally, the optimized conditions for maximum fluorescence quenching were determined using numerical optimization where the goal was to maximize the quenching response (
                           Fig. S4
                        ). The optimal levels were found to be pH of 8.5, S,N-GQDs concentration of 0.35 mg/mL, buffer volume of 3 mL, and an incubation time of 3 min. The overlay plot showed the design space where the desired conditions were met (
                           Fig. S4
                        ).

The method also demonstrated excellent linearity in plasma matrix over the same concentration range of 0.5 to 4.0 μg/mL (
                           Table S3
                        ). The plasma calibration curve exhibited a coefficient of determination of 0.9993, indicating outstanding linearity in the biological matrix. The regression equation obtained for the plasma samples was y = 1.1769x + 0.4968, where y represents the quenching efficiency (F0/F) and x is the concentration of glimepiride in μg/mL. This matrix-matched calibration curve was subsequently employed for the accurate quantification of glimepiride in plasma samples, in accordance with bioanalytical method validation guidelines.

Selectivity is another important aspect of method validation. The results indicated that there was no significant interference from common pharmaceutical excipients or ions, thus confirming the high selectivity of the developed method (Fig. 4
                        ). Furthermore, standard addition technique was also employed by spiking the drug formulation with different concentrations of glimepiride, and the recovery data were within the acceptance limits, demonstrating the absence of matrix effects (
                           Table S4
                        ).

The applicability of the method was further demonstrated by determining glimepiride in human plasma samples. Glimepiride was efficiently extracted from the spiked plasma samples using a simple protein precipitation procedure. Using the matrix-matched calibration curve, different plasma samples spiked with glimepiride at three different concentrations (low, medium, and high) were analyzed, and the recovery values were found to be within the acceptance criteria, ranging from 93.80 to 105.73 % (
                           Table S5
                        ). Besides, the CV% values were less than 7 %, indicating the high accuracy and precision of the method for the analysis of glimepiride in biological matrices.
